PEARLS:
1.
Hyperventilation is not recommended for head-injury patients who do not have
symptoms of herniation syndrome, as auto-regulatory mechanisms are intact and
hyperventilation may worsen cerebral perfusion pressure.
2.
One of the most important indicators of worsening head injury is a change in
LOC and / or GCS.
3.
Increased ICP may cause hypertension and bradycardia (Cushing’s response).
4.
Hypotension usually indicates injury or shock unrelated to the head injury and
should be treated aggressively to maintain adequate cerebral perfusion.
5.
Supine positioning may also increase ICP transiently. The patient may benefit
from a reverse Trendelenburg position; however, it may reduce cerebral blood
flow, especially if the head is elevated greater than 30°. If the patient is
immobilized to a backboard, slightly elevate (15° or less) the head end of the
board.

